===Glyph origin===
According to one theory, this is a variant form of [[氐]].

{{ja-etym-kokuji}} which hypothesized to have been invented in Goguryeo. Earliest usage example appeared in the ''{{w|Gwanggaeto Stele}}'', erected in 414 as "幹弖利城", a name of the fortress.
As the first example in Japan, appeared in the {{w|Inariyama Sword|Inariyama burial-mound sword}}, 471 as names of ancestors of the local ruler, "弖已加利獲居 (''Teyokariwake'' < ''Teyo<sub>2</sub>kariwake<sub>2</sub>'')" and "半弖比 (''Hatehi'' < ''Patepi<sub>1</sub>'')".

